In[3]:
(x_training, y_training), (x_test, y_test) = cifar10.load_data()

Normalize data

*(Code adopted from Lesson 9)

In[4]:
    # Scale pixal values (Keep shape 32x32, 3 channels for rgb)
x_train = x_training.astype('float32') / 255.0
x_test = x_test.astype('float32') / 255.0

    # One-hot encode targets
y_train = to_categorical(y_training, 10)
y_test = to_categorical(y_test, 10)

    # Confirm shapes
print("Training set:", x_train.shape)
print("Test set:", x_test.shape)
print("Number of classes:", y_train.shape[1])

Build simple ANN model

In[6]:
    # Build model
ANN_model = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dense(10, activation='softmax')])

ANN_model.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy'])

Train and Evaluate ANN model

In[17]:
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)

history_ANN = ANN_model.fit(
    x_train, y_train,
    epochs=100,
    batch_size=256,
    validation_split=0.1,
    verbose=2,
    callbacks=[early_stop])

    # Evaluate model on test data
test_loss, test_acc = ANN_model.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print(f"Test Accuracy: {test_acc:.4f}")

Build a CNN model

*(Code adapted from Lesson 9 and live class examples)

In[11]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D
from tensorflow.keras.utils import plot_model
from IPython.display import Image

    # Build model
CNN_model = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(32, 32, 3)),
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.25),
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
    Dropout(0.25),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(10, activation='softmax')])

CNN_model.compile(optimizer='adam',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    # Display Model
plot_model(CNN_model, to_file='CNN_layers.png', show_shapes=True, show_layer_names=True)
#display(Image('CNN_layers.png'))

ANN vs. CNN Comparison
Model Structures


    

  • ANN: Flatten  Dense(128)  Dropout(0.5)  Dense(64)  Softmax
    • 

  • CNN: Conv2D(32)  MaxPool  Dropout(0.25)  Conv2D(64)  MaxPool  Dropout(0.25)  Flatten  Dense(128)  Dropout(0.5)  Softmax
    • 



Validation Accuracy


    

  • ANN Validation Accuracy: 0.36
    • 

  • CNN Validation Accuracy: 0.74
    • 



Final Accuracy


    

  • ANN Test Accuracy: 0.37
    • 

  • CNN Test Accuracy: 0.72
    • 



Observations


    

  • Both models are overfit, as the test metrics are slightly below metrics for training (but within 0.05 range).
    • 

  • The CNN model outperforms the ANN significantly on image data due to its ability to capture spatial hierarchies using convolutional filters.
    • 

  • The ANN model is simpler, but overfit quickly and plateaus due to the fully connected nature, which ignores spatial features.
    • 

  • CNN generalizes better and exhibits higher stability across epochs.
    • 



Conclusion


    

  • ANNs are faster and are still useful for low-dimensional data, but they lack the inductive bias that makes CNNs effective for visual patterns.
    • 

  • CNNs are the preferred architecture for image classification tasks like CIFAR-10.
    • 



Next steps


    

  • Correcting overfitting and increasing accuracy should be accomplished with some hypertuning, but the computational time was markedly longer using CNN.
    • 

  • I attempted to use a TPU, but was unable to connect. Running the models with a TPU runtime would aid in fine tuning the CNN.
    •
